## Natural vs. Human Causes of Climate Change

### Natural Climate Drivers

Natural processes influencing climate include:

- **Volcanic eruptions:** Release aerosols and GHGs, causing short-term cooling or warming.
- **Solar radiation variations:** Changes in the sun’s energy output can influence climate.
- **Orbital cycles (Milankovitch cycles):** Affect long-term climate patterns over tens of thousands of years.
- **Oceanic cycles:** Phenomena like El Niño and La Niña cause regional and temporal climate variability ([AA Environment, 2024](https://aaenvironment.com/human-vs-natural-causes-of-climate-change-explained/); [NASA, 2024](https://climate.nasa.gov/scientific_consensus/)).

While these natural factors have historically driven climate variability, their impact in recent decades has been overshadowed by human activities.

### Evidence for Human Dominance

Multiple lines of evidence, including climate models, paleoclimate data (ice cores, tree rings), and direct observations, show that the rapid warming observed since the mid-20th century is overwhelmingly due to human activities:

- The rate of current warming is about ten times faster than natural warming events following the last Ice Age.
- The stratosphere has cooled while the troposphere has warmed, a pattern consistent with GHG-induced warming rather than solar changes ([Scientific American, 2024](https://www.scientificamerican.com/article/science-behind-climate-change/)).
- Climate models that include only natural forcings fail to replicate the observed warming trend; only models including anthropogenic GHG emissions match observations ([NASA, 2024](https://climate.nasa.gov/scientific_consensus/)).

The scientific consensus is robust: human activities are the dominant cause of recent climate change ([NASA, 2024](https://climate.nasa.gov/scientific_consensus/); [EPA, 2024](https://www.epa.gov/climatechange-science/causes-climate-change)).

