## Consequences of Climate Change

### Temperature Rise and Global Warming

Since 1880, Earth's average surface temperature has increased by approximately 1.9°F (1.1°C), with the last decade being the warmest on record. The year 2024 was the hottest year recorded globally, largely attributable to anthropogenic climate change ([BBC News, 2024](https://www.bbc.com/news/science-environment-24021772)).

### Melting Ice and Rising Sea Levels

Warming accelerates the melting of glaciers and ice caps, which hold 70–75% of the world's freshwater. Meltwater contributes to rising sea levels, threatening coastal communities and ecosystems. The ice-albedo feedback amplifies warming: as reflective ice melts, darker ocean water absorbs more heat, further increasing temperatures ([National Geographic Society, 2024](https://education.nationalgeographic.org/resource/greenhouse-effect-our-planet/); [NASA, 2024](https://climate.nasa.gov/scientific_consensus/)).

### Extreme Weather and Ecosystem Impacts

Climate change increases the frequency and intensity of extreme weather events such as heatwaves, droughts, wildfires, hurricanes, and floods. These changes disrupt ecosystems, agriculture, water resources, and human health ([NASA, 2024](https://science.nasa.gov/climate-change/what-is-climate-change/)).

---

## Feedback Mechanisms and Climate Sensitivity

Climate feedbacks amplify or dampen the effects of initial warming:

- **Positive feedbacks:** Water vapor increases as temperatures rise, enhancing the greenhouse effect; melting ice reduces albedo; thawing permafrost releases methane.
- **Negative feedbacks:** Increased cloud cover can reflect sunlight, potentially cooling the surface.

Overall, feedbacks have a net positive effect, roughly tripling the warming caused by direct GHG forcing ([Climate Science Special Report, 2017](https://science2017.globalchange.gov/chapter/2/)).

---

## Mitigation and Adaptation

### Reducing Greenhouse Gas Emissions

Mitigation strategies include:

- Transitioning to renewable energy sources.
- Enhancing energy efficiency.
- Reducing deforestation and promoting reforestation.
- Changing agricultural practices to reduce methane and nitrous oxide emissions.
- Supporting technological innovations to capture and store carbon ([National Geographic Society, 2024](https://education.nationalgeographic.org/resource/greenhouse-effect-our-planet/); [UNEP, 2024](https://www.unep.org/news-and-stories/story/how-do-greenhouse-gases-actually-warm-planet)).

### Adaptation Measures

Communities must also prepare for unavoidable climate impacts through infrastructure resilience, disaster preparedness, and sustainable resource management ([NASA, 2024](https://www.nasa.gov/earth)).

---

## Conclusion

Climate change operates primarily through the enhanced greenhouse effect, where increased concentrations of greenhouse gases—largely from human activities—trap more heat in Earth's atmosphere, leading to global warming and associated climatic disruptions. While natural processes contribute to climate variability, the unprecedented rate and magnitude of recent changes are overwhelmingly driven by anthropogenic emissions. Understanding these mechanisms is critical for developing effective mitigation and adaptation strategies to safeguard the planet's future.

